## Context

User feedback during smoke test:

```
$ uv run maiba scan -v -i tests/fixtures/ArchiveCCS.ris -o test4.ris --cache
maiba: error: unrecognized arguments: -v
```

`-v` was on the top-level parser only, so it had to come BEFORE
`scan`. Most modern CLIs put verbosity flags after the verb
(`git commit -v`, `cargo build --verbose`, `npm install --verbose`),
which is what the user typed.

## Why not parents= on both top and sub

argparse footgun: when a subparser uses `parents=[parent]` AND the
top-level parser also defines `-v`, the subparser's default value
clobbers the top-level value when the subcommand is parsed. So
`maiba -v scan ...` would silently produce verbosity=0 even when
the top-level `-v` was given.

Workarounds (parse_known_args, post-merge values) are more code
than the value adds. Easier: put `-v` only on subparsers.

## Actions

1. **`src/maiba/cli.py`** —
   - Drop `-v/--verbose` from the top-level parser.
   - Define a small `verbose_parent` (add_help=False) with `-v`
     and inherit it via `parents=[verbose_parent]` on each
     subparser (`scan`, `clear-cache`).
   - In `main()`, use `getattr(args, "verbose", 0)` because the
     no-args / help-only path doesn't include the attribute.

## Trade-off

- Lost: `maiba -v scan ...` (now an error).
- Gained: `maiba scan -v ...` (matches user intuition and modern CLI norm).

## Exit criteria

- `make test` green; existing 74 tests pass.
- `make lint` green.
- `uv run maiba scan -v ...` shows INFO logs (manual eyeball).
- `uv run maiba scan -vv ...` shows DEBUG logs.
- `uv run maiba` (no args) prints help, no crash.
